In programming, you often need to convert data from one type to another. This is known as typecasting.

Your task is to write a program that reads a double-precision floating-point number 
(a number with a decimal part) from the user and converts it into an integer. 
When converting a double to an integer, the program should drop (truncate) the decimal portion completely, without rounding up or down.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Input Format

A single line containing a double-precision floating-point number, N

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Constraints

−10^9 ≤N≤10^9

The input will always be a valid numeric value.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Output Format

Print a single integer representing the truncated value of the input.
